First Nearctic record of Hydrellia albilabris (Meigen) (Diptera: Ephydridae), a leafminer of duckweed (Araceae: Lemnoideae), with comments on related species
Article
Full-text available
  • May 2019
  • Charles Eiseman
  • Tadeusz Zatwarnicki
Hydrellia albilabris (Meigen) (Diptera: Ephydridae) is recorded in the Nearctic Region for the first time. Its biology and immature stages are documented, and other miners in duckweeds (Araceae: Lemnoideae) are discussed. One new combination is proposed: Hydrellia jinpingensis (Zhang, Yang, and Hayashi) is transferred from Cavatorella.

Checklist of the family Ephydridae of Finland (Insecta, Diptera)
Article
Full-text available
  • Sep 2014
  • Tadeusz Zatwarnicki
  • Jere Kahanp
A checklist of 112 species of shore flies (Ephydridae, Diptera) recorded from Finland is presented. Comparing this to the list of Hackman (1980), 52 changes are made: 25 species are added (all but one recorded after 1980), 18 misidentifications are deleted, 5 junior synonyms are replaced and 5 updated generic combinations are given.

Checklist of the Diptera of Finland (2014)
Archived project
Publishing an updated checklist of Finnish Diptera to replace the list of Hackman (1980).
View
Cost-effective Biodiversity Discovery
Project
The museums are full of unprocessed specimens and surveys continue to add to the backlog. The most specimen-rich and often species-rich taxa are particularly neglected. Species-level sorting for these taxa is often not even attempted or delegated to parataxonomists. This is where DNA barcodes are useful for presorting as long as they can be obtained in large numbers and at low cost. In this project, we develop such techniques. DirectPCR skips DNA extraction, NGS barcoding lowers the barcoding cost to ca 40 cents per specimen, and barcoding now no longer requires expensive equipment (see MinION paper). Fortunately, presorting with NGS barcodes yields results that are largely congruent with morphology. Congruence is assessed across many taxa, correctly delimited species are imaged, and then identified or described.
